recordings.file-name: XC714783-Melospiza melodia mexicana - April 10 2022 - 5.58 am -​ JW.mp3
recordings.rmk:
- "Full *Quino* Show"
- Stereo-recorded (WAV) on a Redmi Note 10S smartphone.
- An airplane (1:55) and many other birds can be heard in the background.
- Being an urban specimen, I deliberately did not filter out the city background noise.
- As of April 3, 2022, Mexico City is under Daylight Saving Time (DST) (this means earlier active and noisy city), but this recording timestamp is still 'standard time'.
- Volume gain applied.
- This specimen is the same one as in other of my recordings, I call it *Quino*.
- *Quino* likes to come to a neighbor's same peach-tree and at about the same time every morning (based on the amount of light, I guess).
- This recording is a "full *Quino* show": 23 phrases.  It starts a few seconds before *Quino* arrives at the tree and begins to sing and ends when it finally flies away.
- SInce the usual peach-tree that *Quino* arrives at has become densely populated with new leaves *Quino* chose more distant bougainvillea branches –with less leaves– that the ones he used to sit in.
- Distance from bird to recording device: changes from aprox. 4 m. to (00:35) aprox. 6 m.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Bird was perched 2-3 m above the ground near the top of an isolated box elder (Acer negundo) in an open grassland ~50m from a forest edge. I was only about 5-8 m from the bird and watched the bird through binoculars while recording because I could not see the bill opening. If the bill was opened at all, it was very slight, but the tail and plumage quivered during the vocalizations. Just after 1:34 a male Northern Cardinal chased the bird out of the tree briefly before the juvenile and a second Song Sparrow returned to chase away the Cardinal. After this the juvenile resumed singing while the second sparrow moved away into the grass. 

# Editing #
Adobe Audition FFT filter, 2048 pts, Blackman window, 1 kHz to 14 kHz bandpass.

recordings.rmk:
Singing from atop a small tree on the shore of a still-frozen lake. Another Song Sparrow counter-singing in the background. 

Recorded with Sennheiser ME66 from 10m away. Light filtering of low frequencies. 

Yellow-bellied Sapsucker (at e.g. 4:37 and following) almost seems to be responding to one particular song type whose introductory notes are superficially similar to the sapsucker's call.

Powderhorn Park, Minneapolis, Hennepin, Minnesota
recordings.rmk:
Second individual recorded today. Singing just before dawn from shoreline vegetation along a pond in an urban park.  After the first series of song (around 4:30), the focal bird flew into a deeper section of shoreline vegetation and appeared to chase another bird around.  Some wing noises and rustling vegetation can be heard.  After the altercation, one bird flew back out to a perch and resumed singing.  It may be the same bird or it may have been another bird.

Filtered low frequencies for urban noise.  Recorded with Olympus LS-10S and Sennheiser ME66.  Distance to microphone ~ 5m.
